originalText: Adaptive Design Testing: Test the UI on various devices and simulate different screen sizes by resizing browser windows to ensure consistent functionality and appearance.
Browser Compatibility Testing: Validate UI rendering and functionality across supported browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari) to ensure uniform behavior and visual consistency.

Completion Criteria: Each screen successfully verified to ensure the software meets usability standards and is user-friendly
  • Verify All Navigations.
  • Verify component state.
  • Verify input format and validation for each field.

Completion Criteria: Each screen to ensure only accepted users can access features corresponding to their role.
  • Verify access to functions for all approved roles and disapproved roles.
Interaction Flow Testing: Verify seamless navigation by testing keyboard-based tab sequences, mouse interactions, and shortcut keys for moving between fields and screens.
Message and Error Handling Testing: Confirm that system messages, validation errors, and notifications) are presented clearly, in the correct position, and without impacting the UI layout.

Objective: Ensure that only authorized users can access the system.
  • Authentication: Ensure that only authorized users can access the system.
  • Authorization: Ensure user accounts are authorized, allowing access to features corresponding to their role.
  • Data security: The system must protect personal and critical information from unauthorized access.

Objective:
  • The user interface is designed similar to the design mockup. Any changes to the user interface need confirmation from the end user or supervisor.
  • Verify errors during interactions and provide on-screen feedback messages for users.
Style Uniformity Testing: Ensure consistent application of fonts, colors, icons, and design elements across all pages, forms, and dashboards to maintain a unified aesthetic.
UI Layout Validation: Manually inspect each interface to confirm proper alignment, spacing, and visual hierarchy across different screen resolutions and devices.

Assignment Management Workflow: Confirm that a teacher can create an assignment, students can submit their work, and the teacher can grade and provide feedback, with parents receiving updates on the submission status.

HRM Payroll Processing: Validate that the HRM module accurately calculates teacher salaries based on hours taught, generates a clear payroll report, and allows administrators to review and approve payments.

Student Enrollment Process: Verify that an administrator can successfully register a new student, assign them to a class, and send a confirmation notification to parents, with all steps completed accurately and without errors.
All text, including instructions and notifications, is presented in Vietnamese to cater to the primary user base.
Checking all the system's functionalities to ensure that each feature works correctly under various scenarios and error conditions.

Conduct black-box testing to verify system behavior without knowledge of internal code structure, using the following methods:

  • Equivalence Partitioning: Divide input data into valid and invalid classes and test representative values
  • Boundary Value Analysis: Test boundary conditions for fields such as class size limits, assignment file sizes, and payroll calculation inputs.
  • End-to-End Testing: Validate complete workflows, such as student enrollment → class assignment → attendance tracking → grading.

Validate that the Minh Viet Educational System operates as intended by thoroughly testing all key business processes, user interactions, navigation, data input/output, processing, and response handling for each functional module.
Validate the system as a whole to ensure all components work together as intended in a fully integrated environment.

Verify the following:

  • Navigation within the Minh Viet Educational System aligns with educational workflows and requirements, including:
    • Seamless transitions between screens
    • Smooth field-to-field navigation within forms
    • Support for multiple access methods, including tab keys, mouse clicks, and keyboard shortcuts for efficient interaction.
  • UI elements adhere to visual and interactive standards:
    • Consistent size, style, color, and positioning across all components for a cohesive user experience.
    • Proper focus behavior for interactive elements to support accessibility and usability.
    • Responsive design that adapts effectively to various devices

• All UI elements and layouts render accurately and uniformly across supported browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, Safari) and devices.
  • Navigation flows, interactive components, and user inputs operate smoothly without errors or delays.
  • No visual defects, such as misaligned elements, overlapping components, or distorted layouts, are present.
  • Localized text Vietnamese is displayed correctly without causing layout issues, truncation, or overflow.

• All test cases related to functional requirements have been executed successfully.
  • All critical and high-severity defects have been resolved and retested.
  • Test coverage for functional modules reaches at least 80%.

• Complex UI components, such as dynamic dashboards or file upload interfaces, may require additional testing to ensure accessibility compliance and proper functionality.
  • Vietnamese text, including diacritics, must be thoroughly tested to prevent rendering issues or layout disruptions due to varying text lengths.

• Features reliant on external integrations must be tested using sandbox or mock environments to simulate real-world conditions.
  • Complex workflows, such as student registration → class assignment → attendance tracking → grading, must be tested end-to-end to ensure seamless operation.
  • Localization and language support Vietnamese must be verified for UI elements, notifications, and reports.

Acceptance Testing is a phase in the software testing process where a system undergoes evaluation for acceptability. The objective is to assess the system's compliance with business requirements and determine its suitability for delivery. In this context, a checklist will be employed as a replacement for Acceptance Testing, alongside some examples of Acceptance Testing. The content of the Checklist is shown in the table below:

This Test Plan delineates the comprehensive strategy, scope, and methodology for testing the Minh Viet Educational System platform. The primary aim is to thoroughly verify the system’s functionality, stability, performance, security, and user-friendliness to ensure it aligns with all defined requirements and operates seamlessly under anticipated operational conditions before its official launch.
This document serves as a roadmap for the testing process and includes the following details:

This section specifies the features and requirements to be tested for the Minh Viet Educational System. It encompasses both functional components ,business logic and non-functional aspects.These test items are derived from system specifications, user requirements, and acceptance criteria outlined in the project documentation. Testing will cover critical workflows, including student management, classroom scheduling, assignment handling, parent-teacher communication, and administrative operations, alongside non-functional attributes such as system performance, security, and user experience.
Typically involves stakeholders or end users to ensure the system is functional, usable, and meets acceptance criteria.
Typically performed by the tester on the user screen after each iteration.

UI elements adhere to visual and interactive standards:
  • Consistent size, style, color, and positioning across all components for a cohesive user experience.
  • Proper focus behavior for interactive elements to support accessibility and usability.
  • Responsive design that adapts effectively to various devices
Unit tests are created by the developer and test scripts are written for the important methods in the project. There is no specific documentation for the unit tests.
